          "body": "The chapter's architecture is twin divine initiatives that converge. Cornelius prays at the ninth hour and receives an angel (10:3); Peter prays at the sixth hour the next day and receives a trance (10:9-10). Neither man is seeking the other. Neither sees the whole picture. God is operating at both ends of the coastal road simultaneously, orchestrating an encounter that neither party would have engineered. Cornelius would not have summoned an apostle on his own initiative; Peter would not have entered a Gentile centurion's house under any circumstance he could imagine. The chapter is a tutorial in providence — God advances His mission through prayerful servants who do not yet see how their obediences will connect."
